    "body": "### Problem\n\nI'm editing a Rust source file, with LSP generating virtualtext errors. Tree-sitter is installed, with `highlight ={ enabled = true}`.\n\nIn this example recording, I've navigated to line 1741 and typed `dd` once (then typed `u` to undo the changes):\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4e4f16b8-08a2-4965-af79-30c3969a6bc3\n\nIt looks as if `dd` deleted two lines instead of one. However if I use `:redraw!`, it's clear that only one line was deleted: \n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9d248941-0147-4629-b02d-83d8c7032e44\n\nOne more interesting thing is that after typing `dd`, lines 1741 and 1742 disappear from the line board on the left.\n\nSame issue also happens with the WSL (running Fedora 41) and the Windows terminal:\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a4cdab62-a896-44ae-b954-fc44654eac08\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nExtract the attached file - it contains\n* a `mod.rs` source file (for tree-sitter to parse)\n* a `minimal.lua` file that loads the source file and adds virtualtext and other decorations provided by the `rust-analyzer` LSP\n\n[ts-lsp-virtualtext.tgz](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19622723/ts-lsp-virtualtext.tgz)\n\nRun it with `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua`.\n\nNavigate to line 1741, ensuring that lines 1739-1748 are visible _on the lower half_ of the screen.\nType `dd` on line 1741 - it will look as if both `info!...` and `return Ok...` were deleted.\n\n`:refresh!` will force redrawing the virtualtext and fix the issue.\n\nIt seems like the issue is more likely to happen if there's overflow/wrapping of virtualtext, and if the virtualtext is on the lower half of the screen.\n\n<img width=\"882\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4f8a4a3d-61b2-4f77-bc14-868b1ec5b0f5\" />\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nTyping `dd` on line 1741 deletes just one line (`info!...`), and the next line (`return Ok...`) moves up one line.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.0 (release build)\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno (vim 9.1.754)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15.4; Fedora Linux 41\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nTerminal.app (macOS), modern Windows Terminal (Fedora 41 on WSL)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nOfficial Github release page",
